  "text": "Synovial sarcoma is the most common malignant tumor of the lower-limb extremities and affects predominantly young patients. On MRI, synovial sarcoma appears as a welldefined lobulated subcutaneous lesion with a signal intensity similar to the muscle intensity on T1-weighted images and homogeneously hyperintense to the fat and the muscle on T2-weighted images. Synovial sarcoma is enhanced after gadolinium administration, which is particularly important for the differentiation from cystic lesions. Peripheral calcifications may be present, leading to decreased intensity foci on T1-and T2-weighted sequences [CITATION_1] .",
